properties.description: Mouse button mask identifier, one of or a bitwise combination of the BUTTON_MASK_* constants in [@GlobalScope].

properties.name: global_position
properties.description: Mouse position relative to the current [Viewport] when used in [method Control._gui_input], otherwise is at 0,0.

properties.name: position
properties.description: Mouse local position relative to the [Viewport]. If used in [method Control._gui_input] the position is relative to the current [Control] which is under the mouse.

RichTextLabel.name: RichTextLabel
RichTextLabel.description:
Rich text can contain custom text, fonts, images and some basic formatting. The label manages these as an internal tag stack. It also adapts itself to given width/heights.
		Note that assignments to [member bbcode_text] clear the tag stack and reconstruct it from the property's contents. Any edits made to [member bbcode_text] will erase previous edits made from other manual sources such as [method append_bbcode] and the [code]push_*[/code] / [method pop] methods.

methods.name: add_image
methods.description: Adds an image's opening and closing tags to the tag stack.

methods.name: add_text
methods.description: Adds raw non-bbcode-parsed text to the tag stack.

methods.name: append_bbcode
methods.description: Parses [code]bbcode[/code] and adds tags to the tag stack as needed. Returns the result of the parsing, [code]OK[/code] if successful.

methods.name: clear
methods.description: Clears the tag stack and sets [member bbcode_text] to an empty string.

methods.name: get_line_count
methods.description: Returns the total number of newlines in the tag stack's text tags. Considers wrapped text as one line.

methods.name: get_total_character_count
methods.description: Returns the total number of characters from text tags. Does not include bbcodes.

methods.name: get_v_scroll
methods.description: Returns the vertical scrollbar.

methods.name: get_visible_line_count
methods.description: Returns the number of visible lines.

methods.name: newline
methods.description: Adds a newline tag to the tag stack.

methods.name: parse_bbcode
methods.description: The assignment version of [method append_bbcode]. Clears the tag stack and inserts the new content. Returns [code]OK[/code] if parses [code]bbcode[/code] successfully.

methods.name: pop
methods.description: Terminates the current tag. Use after [code]push_*[/code] methods to close bbcodes manually. Does not need to follow [code]add_*[/code] methods.

methods.name: push_align
methods.description: Adds a [code][right][/code] tag to the tag stack.

methods.name: push_cell
methods.description: Adds a [code][cell][/code] tag to the tag stack. Must be inside a [table] tag. See [method push_table] for details.

methods.name: push_color
methods.description: Adds a [code][color][/code] tag to the tag stack.

methods.name: push_font
methods.description: Adds a [code][font][/code] tag to the tag stack. Overrides default fonts for its duration.

methods.name: push_indent
methods.description: Adds an [code][indent][/code] tag to the tag stack. Multiplies "level" by current tab_size to determine new margin length.

methods.name: push_list
methods.description: Adds a list tag to the tag stack. Similar to the bbcodes [code][ol][/code] or [code][ul][/code], but supports more list types. Not fully implemented!

methods.name: push_meta
methods.description: Adds a meta tag to the tag stack. Similar to the bbcode [code][url=something]{text}[/url][/code], but supports non-[String] metadata types.

methods.name: push_table
methods.description: Adds a [code][table=columns][/code] tag to the tag stack.

methods.name: push_underline
methods.description: Adds a [code][u][/code] tag to the tag stack.

methods.name: remove_line
methods.description: Removes a line of content from the label. Returns [code]true[/code] if the line exists.

methods.name: scroll_to_line
methods.description: Scrolls the window's top line to match [code]line[/code].

methods.name: set_table_column_expand
methods.description:
Edits the selected columns expansion options. If [code]expand[/code] is [code]true[/code], the column expands in proportion to its expansion ratio versus the other columns' ratios.
				For example, 2 columns with ratios 3 and 4 plus 70 pixels in available width would expand 30 and 40 pixels, respectively.
				Columns with a [code]false[/code] expand will not contribute to the total ratio.

signals.name: meta_clicked
signals.description: Triggered when the user clicks on content between [url] tags. If the meta is defined in text, e.g. [code][url={"data"="hi"}]hi[/url][/code], then the parameter for this signal will be a [String] type. If a particular type or an object is desired, the [method push_meta] method must be used to manually insert the data into the tag stack.

signals.name: meta_hover_ended
signals.description: Triggers when the mouse exits a meta tag.

signals.name: meta_hover_started
signals.description: Triggers when the mouse enters a meta tag.

properties.name: bbcode_enabled
properties.description: If [code]true[/code] the label uses BBCode formatting. Default value: [code]false[/code].

properties.name: bbcode_text
properties.description: The label's text in BBCode format. Is not representative of manual modifications to the internal tag stack. Erases changes made by other methods when edited.

properties.name: meta_underlined
properties.description: If [code]true[/code], the label underlines meta tags such as [url]{text}[/url]. Default value: [code]true[/code].

properties.name: override_selected_font_color
properties.description: If [code]true[/code] the label uses the custom font color. Default value: [code]false[/code].

properties.name: percent_visible
properties.description: The text's visibility, as a [float] between 0.0 and 1.0.

properties.name: scroll_active
properties.description: If [code]true[/code], the scrollbar is visible. Does not block scrolling completely. See [method scroll_to_line]. Default value: [code]true[/code].

properties.name: scroll_following
properties.description: If [code]true[/code], the window scrolls down to display new content automatically. Default value: [code]false[/code].

properties.name: selection_enabled
properties.description: If [code]true[/code], the label allows text selection.

properties.name: tab_size
properties.description: The number of spaces associated with a single tab length. Does not affect "\t" in text tags, only indent tags.

properties.name: text
properties.description:
The raw text of the label.
			When set, clears the tag stack and adds a raw text tag to the top of it. Does not parse bbcodes. Does not modify [member bbcode_text].

properties.name: visible_characters
properties.description: The restricted number of characters to display in the label.

Label.name: Label
Label.brief_description: Displays plain text in a line or wrapped inside a rectangle. For formatted text, use [RichTextLabel].
Label.description:
Label displays plain text on the screen. It gives you control over the horizontal and vertical alignment, and can wrap the text inside the node's bounding rectangle. It doesn't support bold, italics or other formatting. For that, use [RichTextLabel] instead.
		Note that contrarily to most other [Control]s, Label's [member Control.mouse_filter] defaults to MOUSE_FILTER_IGNORE (i.e. it doesn't react to mouse input events).

methods.name: get_line_count
methods.description: Returns the amount of lines of text the Label has.

methods.name: get_line_height
methods.description: Returns the font size in pixels.

methods.name: get_total_character_count
methods.description: Returns the total length of the text.

methods.name: get_visible_line_count
methods.description: Returns the number of lines shown. Useful if the [code]Label[/code] 's height cannot currently display all lines.

constants.name: ALIGN_LEFT
constants.description: Align rows to the left (default).

constants.name: ALIGN_CENTER
constants.description: Align rows centered.

constants.name: ALIGN_RIGHT
constants.description: Align rows to the right (default).

constants.name: ALIGN_FILL
constants.description: Expand row whitespaces to fit the width.

constants.name: VALIGN_TOP
constants.description: Align the whole text to the top.

constants.name: VALIGN_CENTER
constants.description: Align the whole text to the center.

constants.name: VALIGN_BOTTOM
constants.description: Align the whole text to the bottom.

constants.name: VALIGN_FILL
constants.description: Align the whole text by spreading the rows.

properties.name: align
properties.description: Controls the text's horizontal align. Supports left, center, right, and fill, or justify. Set it to one of the [code]ALIGN_*[/code] constants.

properties.name: autowrap
properties.description: If [code]true[/code], wraps the text inside the node's bounding rectangle. If you resize the node, it will change its height automatically to show all the text. Default: false.

properties.name: clip_text
properties.description: If [code]true[/code], the Label only shows the text that fits inside its bounding rectangle. It also lets you scale the node down freely.

properties.name: lines_skipped
properties.description: The node ignores the first [code]lines_skipped[/code] lines before it starts to display text.

properties.name: max_lines_visible
properties.description: Limits the lines of text the node shows on screen.

properties.name: percent_visible
properties.description: Limits the count of visible characters. If you set [code]percent_visible[/code] to 50, only up to half of the text's characters will display on screen. Useful to animate the text in a dialog box.

properties.name: text
properties.description: The text to display on screen.

properties.name: uppercase
properties.description: If [code]true[/code], all the text displays as UPPERCASE.

properties.name: valign
properties.description: Controls the text's vertical align. Supports top, center, bottom, and fill. Set it to one of the [code]VALIGN_*[/code] constants.

properties.name: visible_characters
properties.description: Restricts the number of characters to display. Set to -1 to disable.

VisibilityNotifier2D.name: VisibilityNotifier2D
VisibilityNotifier2D.brief_description: Detects when the node is visible on screen.
VisibilityNotifier2D.description: The VisibilityNotifier2D detects when it is visible on the screen. It also notifies when its bounding rectangle enters or exits the screen or a viewport.

methods.name: is_on_screen
methods.description: If [code]true[/code] the bounding rectangle is on the screen.

signals.name: screen_entered
signals.description: Emitted when the VisibilityNotifier2D enters the screen.

signals.name: screen_exited
signals.description: Emitted when the VisibilityNotifier2D exits the screen.

signals.name: viewport_entered
signals.description: Emitted when the VisibilityNotifier2D enters a [Viewport]'s view.

signals.name: viewport_exited
signals.description: Emitted when the VisibilityNotifier2D exits a [Viewport]'s view.

properties.name: rect
properties.description: The VisibilityNotifier2D's bounding rectangle.

GridMap.name: GridMap
GridMap.description:
GridMap lets you place meshes on a grid interactively. It works both from the editor and can help you create in-game level editors.
		GridMaps use a [MeshLibrary] which contain a list of tiles: meshes with materials plus optional collisions and extra elements.
		A GridMap contains a collection of cells. Each grid cell refers to a [MeshLibrary] item. All cells in the map have the same dimensions.
		A GridMap is split into a sparse collection of octants for efficient rendering and physics processing. Every octant has the same dimensions and can contain several cells.

methods.name: clear
methods.description: Clear all cells.

methods.name: get_cell_item
methods.description: The [MeshLibrary] item index located at the grid-based X, Y and Z coordinates. If the cell is empty, [INVALID_CELL_ITEM] will be returned.

methods.name: get_cell_item_orientation
methods.description: The orientation of the cell at the grid-based X, Y and Z coordinates. -1 is retuned if the cell is empty.

methods.name: get_meshes
methods.description: Array of [Transform] and [Mesh] references corresponding to the non empty cells in the grid. The transforms are specified in world space.

methods.name: get_used_cells
methods.description: Array of [Vector3] with the non empty cell coordinates in the grid map.

methods.name: set_cell_item
methods.description:
Set the mesh index for the cell referenced by its grid-based X, Y and Z coordinates.
				A negative item index will clear the cell.
				Optionally, the item's orientation can be passed.

constants.name: INVALID_CELL_ITEM
constants.description: Invalid cell item that can be used in [method set_cell_item] to clear cells (or represent an empty cell in [method get_cell_item]).

properties.name: cell_center_x
properties.description: If [code]true[/code] grid items are centered on the X axis.

properties.name: cell_center_y
properties.description: If [code]true[/code] grid items are centered on the Y axis.

properties.name: cell_center_z
properties.description: If [code]true[/code] grid items are centered on the Z axis.

properties.name: cell_octant_size
properties.description: The size of each octant measured in number of cells. This applies to all three axis.

properties.name: cell_size
properties.description: The dimensions of the grid's cells.

properties.name: theme
properties.description: The assigned [MeshLibrary].

methods.name: has_network_peer
methods.description: Returns true if there is a [NetworkedMultiplayerPeer] set (with [method SceneTree.set_network_peer]).

methods.name: is_network_server
methods.description: Returns true if this SceneTree's [NetworkedMultiplayerPeer] is in server mode (listening for connections).

properties.name: network_peer
properties.description: The peer object to handle the RPC system (effectively enabling networking when set). Depending on the peer itself, the SceneTree will become a network server (check with [method is_network_server()]) and will set root node's network mode to master (see NETWORK_MODE_* constants in [Node]), or it will become a regular peer with root node set to slave. All child nodes are set to inherit the network mode by default. Handling of networking-related events (connection, disconnection, new clients) is done by connecting to SceneTree's signals.

ReferenceRect.name: ReferenceRect
ReferenceRect.description: Reference frame for GUI. It's just like an empty control, except a red box is displayed while editing around its size at all times.

VSplitContainer.name: VSplitContainer
VSplitContainer.description: Vertical split container. See [SplitContainer]. This goes from left to right.

methods.name: bool
methods.description: Cast an [int] value to a boolean value, this method will return true if called with an integer value different to 0 and false in other case.

methods.name: bool
methods.description: Cast a [float] value to a boolean value, this method will return true if called with a floating point value different to 0 and false in other case.

methods.name: bool
methods.description: Cast a [String] value to a boolean value, this method will return true if called with a non empty string and false in other case. Examples: [code]bool('False')[/code] returns true, [code]bool('')[/code]. returns false

AnimatedSprite3D.name: AnimatedSprite3D
AnimatedSprite3D.brief_description: 2D sprite node in 3D world, that can use multiple 2D textures for animation.
AnimatedSprite3D.description: Animations are created using a [SpriteFrames] resource, which can be configured in the editor via the SpriteFrames panel.

methods.name: is_playing
methods.description: Return true if an animation if currently being played.

methods.name: play
methods.description: Play the animation set in parameter. If no parameter is provided, the current animation is played.

methods.name: stop
methods.description: Stop the current animation (does not reset the frame counter).

signals.name: frame_changed
signals.description: Emitted when [member frame] changed.

properties.name: animation
properties.description: The current animation from the [code]frames[/code] resource. If this value changes, the [code]frame[/code] counter is reset.

properties.name: frame
properties.description: The displayed animation frame's index.

properties.name: frames
properties.description: The [SpriteFrames] resource containing the animation(s).

properties.name: playing
properties.description: If [code]true[/code] the [member animation] is currently playing.

TranslationServer.name: TranslationServer
TranslationServer.brief_description: Server that manages all translations. Translations can be set to it and removed from it.

EditorScript.name: EditorScript
EditorScript.brief_description: Base script that can be used to add extension functions to the editor.
EditorScript.description:
Scripts extending this class and implementing its [code]_run()[/code] method can be executed from the Script Editor's [code]File -> Run[/code] menu option (or by pressing [code]CTRL+Shift+X[/code]) while the editor is running. This is useful for adding custom in-editor functionality to Godot. For more complex additions, consider using [EditorPlugin]s instead. Note that extending scripts need to have [code]tool mode[/code] enabled.
		Example script:
		[codeblock]
		tool
		extends EditorScript

		func _run():
		    print("Hello from the Godot Editor!")
		[/codeblock]
		Note that the script is run in the Editor context, which means the output is visible in the console window started with the Editor (STDOUT) instead of the usual Godot [i]Output[/i] dock.

methods.name: _run
methods.description: This method is executed by the Editor when [code]File -> Run[/code] is used.

methods.name: add_root_node
methods.description:
Adds [code]node[/code] as a child of the root node in the editor context.
				WARNING: The implementation of this method is currently disabled.

methods.name: get_editor_interface
methods.description: Returns the [EditorInterface] singleton instance.

methods.name: get_scene
methods.description: Returns the Editor's currently active scene.

WeakRef.name: WeakRef
WeakRef.brief_description: Holds an [Object], but does not contribute to the reference count if the object is a reference.
WeakRef.description: A weakref can hold a [Reference], without contributing to the reference counter. A weakref can be created from an [Object] using [method @GDScript.weakref]. If this object is not a reference, weakref still works, however, it does not have any effect on the object. Weakrefs are useful in cases where multiple classes have variables that refer to each other. Without weakrefs, using these classes could lead to memory leaks, since both references keep each other from being released. Making part of the variables a weakref can prevent this cyclic dependency, and allows the references to be released.

methods.name: get_ref
methods.description: Returns the [Object] this weakref is referring to.

ARVRInterface.name: ARVRInterface
ARVRInterface.brief_description: Base class for ARVR interface implementation.
ARVRInterface.description:
This class needs to be implemented to make an AR or VR platform available to Godot and these should be implemented as C++ modules or GDNative modules (note that for GDNative the subclass ARVRScriptInterface should be used). Part of the interface is exposed to GDScript so you can detect, enable and configure an AR or VR platform.
		Interfaces should be written in such a way that simply enabling them will give us a working setup. You can query the available interfaces through ARVRServer.

methods.name: get_capabilities
methods.description: Returns a combination of flags providing information about the capabilities of this interface.

methods.name: get_name
methods.description: Returns the name of this interface (OpenVR, OpenHMD, ARKit, etc).

methods.name: get_render_targetsize
methods.description: Returns the resolution at which we should render our intermediate results before things like lens distortion are applied by the VR platform.

methods.name: get_tracking_status
methods.description: If supported, returns the status of our tracking. This will allow you to provide feedback to the user whether there are issues with positional tracking.

methods.name: initialize
methods.description:
Call this to initialize this interface. The first interface that is initialized is identified as the primary interface and it will be used for rendering output.
				After initializing the interface you want to use you then need to enable the AR/VR mode of a viewport and rendering should commence. 
				Note that you must enable the AR/VR mode on the main viewport for any device that uses the main output of Godot such as for mobile VR. 
				If you do this for a platform that handles its own output (such as OpenVR) Godot will show just one eye without distortion on screen. Alternatively you can add a separate viewport node to your scene and enable AR/VR on that viewport and it will be used to output to the HMD leaving you free to do anything you like in the main window such as using a separate camera as a spectator camera or render out something completely different.
				While currently not used you can activate additional interfaces, you may wish to do this if you want to track controllers from other platforms. However at this point in time only one interface can render to an HMD.

methods.name: is_stereo
methods.description: Returns true if the current output of this interface is in stereo.

methods.name: uninitialize
methods.description: Turns the interface off.

constants.name: ARVR_NONE
constants.description: No ARVR capabilities.

constants.name: ARVR_MONO
constants.description: This interface can work with normal rendering output (non-HMD based AR).

constants.name: ARVR_STEREO
constants.description: This interface supports stereoscopic rendering.

constants.name: ARVR_AR
constants.description: This interface support AR (video background and real world tracking).

constants.name: ARVR_EXTERNAL
constants.description: This interface outputs to an external device, if the main viewport is used the on screen output is an unmodified buffer of either the left or right eye (stretched if the viewport size is not changed to the same aspect ratio of get_render_targetsize. Using a separate viewport node frees up the main viewport for other purposes.

constants.name: EYE_MONO
constants.description: Mono output, this is mostly used internally when retrieving positioning information for our camera node or when stereo scopic rendering is not supported.

constants.name: EYE_LEFT
constants.description: Left eye output, this is mostly used internally when rendering the image for the left eye and obtaining positioning and projection information.

constants.name: EYE_RIGHT
constants.description: Right eye output, this is mostly used internally when rendering the image for the right eye and obtaining positioning and projection information.

constants.name: ARVR_NORMAL_TRACKING
constants.description: Tracking is behaving as expected.

constants.name: ARVR_EXCESSIVE_MOTION
constants.description: Tracking is hindered by excessive motion, player is moving faster then tracking can keep up.

constants.name: ARVR_INSUFFICIENT_FEATURES
constants.description: Tracking is hindered by insufficient features, it's too dark (for camera based tracking), player is blocked, etc.

constants.name: ARVR_UNKNOWN_TRACKING
constants.description: We don't know the status of the tracking or this interface does not provide feedback.

constants.name: ARVR_NOT_TRACKING
constants.description: Tracking is not functional (camera not plugged in or obscured, lighthouses turned off, etc.)

properties.name: ar_is_anchor_detection_enabled
properties.description: On an AR interface, is our anchor detection enabled?

properties.name: interface_is_initialized
properties.description: Has this interface been initialized?

properties.name: interface_is_primary
properties.description: Is this our primary interface?

PopupDialog.name: PopupDialog
PopupDialog.description: PopupDialog is a base class for popup dialogs, along with [WindowDialog].

Object.name: Object
Object.brief_description: Base class for all non built-in types.
Object.description:
Base class for all non built-in types. Everything not a built-in type starts the inheritance chain from this class.
		Objects do not manage memory, if inheriting from one the object will most likely have to be deleted manually (call the [method free] function from the script or delete from C++).
		Some derivatives add memory management, such as [Reference] (which keeps a reference count and deletes itself automatically when no longer referenced) and [Node], which deletes the children tree when deleted.
		Objects export properties, which are mainly useful for storage and editing, but not really so much in programming. Properties are exported in [method _get_property_list] and handled in [method _get] and [method _set]. However, scripting languages and C++ have simpler means to export them.
		Objects also receive notifications ([method _notification]). Notifications are a simple way to notify the object about simple events, so they can all be handled together.

methods.name: _get
methods.description: Returns the given property. Returns [code]null[/code] if the [code]property[/code] does not exist.

methods.name: _get_property_list
methods.description: Returns the object's property list as an [Array] of dictionaries. Dictionaries must contain: name:String, type:int (see TYPE_* enum in [@GlobalScope]) and optionally: hint:int (see PROPERTY_HINT_* in [@GlobalScope]), hint_string:String, usage:int (see PROPERTY_USAGE_* in [@GlobalScope]).

methods.name: _init
methods.description: The virtual method called upon initialization.

methods.name: _notification
methods.description: Notify the object internally using an ID.

methods.name: _set
methods.description: Sets a property. Returns [code]true[/code] if the [code]property[/code] exists.

methods.name: add_user_signal
methods.description: Adds a user-defined [code]signal[/code]. Arguments are optional, but can be added as an [Array] of dictionaries, each containing "name" and "type" (from [@GlobalScope] TYPE_*).

methods.name: call
methods.description: Calls the [code]method[/code] on the object and returns a result. Pass parameters as a comma separated list.

methods.name: call_deferred
methods.description: Calls the [code]method[/code] on the object during idle time and returns a result. Pass parameters as a comma separated list.

methods.name: callv
methods.description: Calls the [code]method[/code] on the object and returns a result. Pass parameters as an [Array].

methods.name: can_translate_messages
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if the object can translate strings.

methods.name: connect
methods.description: Connects a [code]signal[/code] to a [code]method[/code] on a [code]target[/code] object. Pass optional [code]binds[/code] to the call. Use [code]flags[/code] to set deferred or one shot connections. See [code]CONNECT_*[/code] constants. A [code]signal[/code] can only be connected once to a [code]method[/code]. It will throw an error if already connected. To avoid this, first use [method is_connected] to check for existing connections.

methods.name: disconnect
methods.description: Disconnects a [code]signal[/code] from a [code]method[/code] on the given [code]target[/code].

methods.name: emit_signal
methods.description: Emits the given [code]signal[/code].

methods.name: free
methods.description: Deletes the object from memory.

methods.name: get
methods.description: Returns a [Variant] for a [code]property[/code].

methods.name: get_class
methods.description: Returns the object's class as a [String].

methods.name: get_incoming_connections
methods.description:
Returns an [Array] of dictionaries with information about signals that are connected to the object.
				Inside each [Dictionary] there are 3 fields:
				- "source" is a reference to signal emitter.
				- "signal_name" is name of connected signal.
				- "method_name" is a name of method to which signal is connected.

methods.name: get_instance_id
methods.description: Returns the object's unique instance ID.

methods.name: get_meta
methods.description: Returns the object's metadata for the given [code]name[/code].

methods.name: get_meta_list
methods.description: Returns the object's metadata as a [PoolStringArray].

methods.name: get_method_list
methods.description: Returns the object's methods and their signatures as an [Array].

methods.name: get_property_list
methods.description: Returns the list of properties as an [Array] of dictionaries. Dictionaries contain: name:String, type:int (see TYPE_* enum in [@GlobalScope]) and optionally: hint:int (see PROPERTY_HINT_* in [@GlobalScope]), hint_string:String, usage:int (see PROPERTY_USAGE_* in [@GlobalScope]).

methods.name: get_script
methods.description: Returns the object's [Script] or [code]null[/code] if one doesn't exist.

methods.name: get_signal_connection_list
methods.description: Returns an [Array] of connections for the given [code]signal[/code].

methods.name: get_signal_list
methods.description: Returns the list of signals as an [Array] of dictionaries.

methods.name: has_meta
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if a metadata is found with the given [code]name[/code].

methods.name: has_method
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if the object contains the given [code]method[/code].

methods.name: has_user_signal
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if the given user-defined [code]signal[/code] exists.

methods.name: is_blocking_signals
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if signal emission blocking is enabled.

methods.name: is_class
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if the object inherits from the given [code]type[/code].

methods.name: is_connected
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if a connection exists for a given [code]signal[/code], [code]target[/code], and [code]method[/code].

methods.name: is_queued_for_deletion
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if the [code]queue_free[/code] method was called for the object.

methods.name: notification
methods.description: Notify the object of something.

methods.name: set
methods.description: Set property into the object.

methods.name: set_block_signals
methods.description: If set to true, signal emission is blocked.

methods.name: set_message_translation
methods.description: Define whether the object can translate strings (with calls to [method tr]). Default is true.

methods.name: set_meta
methods.description: Set a metadata into the object. Metadata is serialized. Metadata can be [i]anything[/i].

methods.name: set_script
methods.description: Set a script into the object, scripts extend the object functionality.

methods.name: tr
methods.description: Translate a message. Only works if message translation is enabled (which it is by default). See [method set_message_translation].

constants.name: NOTIFICATION_POSTINITIALIZE
constants.description: Called right when the object is initialized. Not available in script.

constants.name: NOTIFICATION_PREDELETE
constants.description: Called before the object is about to be deleted.

constants.name: CONNECT_DEFERRED
constants.description: Connect a signal in deferred mode. This way, signal emissions are stored in a queue, then set on idle time.

constants.name: CONNECT_PERSIST
constants.description: Persisting connections are saved when the object is serialized to file.

constants.name: CONNECT_ONESHOT
constants.description: One shot connections disconnect themselves after emission.

PHashTranslation.name: PHashTranslation
PHashTranslation.description: Optimized translation. Uses real-time compressed translations, which results in very small dictionaries.

AudioEffectPhaser.name: AudioEffectPhaser
AudioEffectPhaser.brief_description:
Adds a Phaser audio effect to an Audio bus.
		Combines the original signal with a copy that is slightly out of phase with the original.
AudioEffectPhaser.description: Combines phase-shifted signals with the original signal. The movement of the phase-shifted signals is controlled using a Low Frequency Oscillator.

properties.name: depth
properties.description: Governs how high the filter frequencies sweep. Low value will primarily affect bass frequencies. High value can sweep high into the treble. Value can range from 0.1 to 4. Default value: [code]1[/code].

properties.name: feedback
properties.description: Output percent of modified sound. Value can range from 0.1 to 0.9. Default value: [code]0.7[/code].

properties.name: range_max_hz
properties.description: Determines the maximum frequency affected by the LFO modulations. Value can range from 10 to 10000. Default value: [code]1600hz[/code].

properties.name: range_min_hz
properties.description: Determines the minimum frequency affected by the LFO modulations. Value can range from 10 to 10000. Default value: [code]440hz[/code].

properties.name: rate_hz
properties.description: Adjusts the rate at which the effect sweeps up and down across the frequency range.

Rect2.name: Rect2
Rect2.description: Rect2 consists of a position, a size, and several utility functions. It is typically used for fast overlap tests.

methods.name: Rect2
methods.description: Constructs a [code]Rect2[/code] by position and size.

methods.name: Rect2
methods.description: Constructs a [code]Rect2[/code] by x, y, width, and height.

methods.name: clip
methods.description: Returns the intersection of this [code]Rect2[/code] and b.

methods.name: encloses
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if this [code]Rect2[/code] completely encloses another one.

methods.name: expand
methods.description: Returns this [code]Rect2[/code] expanded to include a given point.

methods.name: get_area
methods.description: Returns the area of the [code]Rect2[/code].

methods.name: grow
methods.description: Returns a copy of the [code]Rect2[/code] grown a given amount of units towards all the sides.

methods.name: grow_individual
methods.description: Returns a copy of the [code]Rect2[/code] grown a given amount of units towards each direction individually.

methods.name: grow_margin
methods.description: Returns a copy of the [code]Rect2[/code] grown a given amount of units towards the [Margin] direction.

methods.name: has_no_area
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if the [code]Rect2[/code] is flat or empty.

methods.name: has_point
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if the [code]Rect2[/code] contains a point.

methods.name: intersects
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if the [code]Rect2[/code] overlaps with another.

methods.name: merge
methods.description: Returns a larger Rect2 that contains this Rect2 and [code]with[/code].

properties.name: end
properties.description: Ending corner.

properties.name: position
properties.description: Position (starting corner).

properties.name: size
properties.description: Size from position to end.

@GDScript.name: @GDScript
@GDScript.description: This contains the list of built-in gdscript functions. Mostly math functions and other utilities. Everything else is expanded by objects.

methods.name: Color8
methods.description:
Returns a 32 bit color with red, green, blue and alpha channels. Each channel has 8 bits of information ranging from 0 to 255.
				[code]r8[/code] red channel
				[code]g8[/code] green channel
				[code]b8[/code] blue channel
				[code]a8[/code] alpha channel
				[codeblock]
				red = Color8(255, 0, 0)
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: ColorN
methods.description:
Returns a color according to the standardised [code]name[/code] with [code]alpha[/code] ranging from 0 to 1.
				[codeblock]
				red = ColorN("red", 1)
				[/codeblock]
				Supported color names:
				"aliceblue", "antiquewhite", "aqua", "aquamarine", "azure", "beige", "bisque", "black", "blanchedalmond", "blue", "blueviolet", "brown", "burlywood", "cadetblue", "chartreuse", "chocolate", "coral", "cornflower", "cornsilk", "crimson", "cyan", "darkblue", "darkcyan", "darkgoldenrod", "darkgray", "darkgreen", "darkkhaki", "darkmagenta", "darkolivegreen", "darkorange", "darkorchid", "darkred", "darksalmon", "darkseagreen", "darkslateblue", "darkslategray", "darkturquoise", "darkviolet", "deeppink", "deepskyblue", "dimgray", "dodgerblue", "firebrick", "floralwhite", "forestgreen", "fuchsia", "gainsboro", "ghostwhite", "gold", "goldenrod", "gray", "webgray", "green", "webgreen", "greenyellow", "honeydew", "hotpink", "indianred", "indigo", "ivory", "khaki", "lavender", "lavenderblush", "lawngreen", "lemonchiffon", "lightblue", "lightcoral", "lightcyan", "lightgoldenrod", "lightgray", "lightgreen", "lightpink", "lightsalmon", "lightseagreen", "lightskyblue", "lightslategray", "lightsteelblue", "lightyellow", "lime", "limegreen", "linen", "magenta", "maroon", "webmaroon", "mediumaquamarine", "mediumblue", "mediumorchid", "mediumpurple", "mediumseagreen", "mediumslateblue", "mediumspringgreen", "mediumturquoise", "mediumvioletred", "midnightblue", "mintcream", "mistyrose", "moccasin", "navajowhite", "navyblue", "oldlace", "olive", "olivedrab", "orange", "orangered", "orchid", "palegoldenrod", "palegreen", "paleturquoise", "palevioletred", "papayawhip", "peachpuff", "peru", "pink", "plum", "powderblue", "purple", "webpurple", "rebeccapurple", "red", "rosybrown", "royalblue", "saddlebrown", "salmon", "sandybrown", "seagreen", "seashell", "sienna", "silver", "skyblue", "slateblue", "slategray", "snow", "springgreen", "steelblue", "tan", "teal", "thistle", "tomato", "turquoise", "violet", "wheat", "white", "whitesmoke", "yellow", "yellowgreen".

methods.name: abs
methods.description:
Returns the absolute value of parameter [code]s[/code]  (i.e. unsigned value, works for integer and float).
				[codeblock]
				# a is 1
				a = abs(-1)
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: acos
methods.description:
Returns the arc cosine of [code]s[/code] in radians. Use to get the angle of cosine [code]s[/code].
				[codeblock]
				# c is 0.523599 or 30 degrees if converted with rad2deg(s)
				c = acos(0.866025)
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: asin
methods.description:
Returns the arc sine of [code]s[/code] in radians. Use to get the angle of sine [code]s[/code].
				[codeblock]
				# s is 0.523599 or 30 degrees if converted with rad2deg(s)
				s = asin(0.5)
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: assert
methods.description:
Assert that the [code]condition[/code] is true. If the [code]condition[/code] is false a fatal error is generated and the program is halted. Useful for debugging to make sure a value is always true.
				[codeblock]
				# Speed should always be between 0 and 20
				speed = -10
				assert(speed < 20) # Is true and program continues
				assert(speed >= 0) # Is false and program stops
				assert(speed >= 0 && speed < 20) # Or combined
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: atan
methods.description:
Returns the arc tangent of [code]s[/code] in radians. Use it to get the angle from an angle's tangent in trigonometry: [code]atan(tan(angle)) == angle[/code].
				The method cannot know in which quadrant the angle should fall. See [method atan2] if you always want an exact angle.
				[codeblock]
				a = atan(0.5) # a is 0.463648
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: atan2
methods.description:
Returns the arc tangent of [code]y/x[/code] in radians. Use to get the angle of tangent [code]y/x[/code]. To compute the value, the method takes into account the sign of both arguments in order to determine the quadrant.
				[codeblock]
				a = atan(0,-1) # a is 3.141593
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: bytes2var
methods.description: Decodes a byte array back to a value.

methods.name: cartesian2polar
methods.description: Converts a 2D point expressed in the cartesian coordinate system (x and y axis) to the polar coordinate system (a distance from the origin and an angle).

methods.name: ceil
methods.description:
Rounds [code]s[/code] upward, returning the smallest integral value that is not less than [code]s[/code].
				[codeblock]
				i = ceil(1.45)  # i is 2
				i = ceil(1.001) # i is 2
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: char
methods.description:
Returns a character as a String of the given ASCII code.
				[codeblock]
				# a is 'A'
				a = char(65)
				# a is 'a'
				a = char(65+32)
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: clamp
methods.description:
Clamps [code]value[/code] and returns a value not less than [code]min[/code] and not more than [code]max[/code].
				[codeblock]
				speed = 1000
				# a is 20
				a = clamp(speed, 1, 20)

				speed = -10
				# a is 1
				a = clamp(speed, 1, 20)
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: convert
methods.description:
Converts from a type to another in the best way possible. The [code]type[/code] parameter uses the enum TYPE_* in [@GlobalScope].
				[codeblock]
				a = Vector2(1, 0)
				# prints 1
				print(a.length())
				a = convert(a, TYPE_STRING)
				# prints 6
				# (1, 0) is 6 characters
				print(a.length())
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: cos
methods.description:
Returns the cosine of angle [code]s[/code] in radians.
				[codeblock]
				# prints 1 and -1
				print(cos(PI*2))
				print(cos(PI))
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: cosh
methods.description:
Returns the hyperbolic cosine of [code]s[/code] in radians.
				[codeblock]
				# prints 1.543081
				print(cosh(1))
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: db2linear
methods.description: Converts from decibels to linear energy (audio).

methods.name: decimals
methods.description:
Returns the position of the first non-zero digit, after the decimal point.
				[codeblock]
				# n is 2
				n = decimals(0.035)
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: dectime
methods.description:
Returns the result of [code]value[/code] decreased by [code]step[/code] * [code]amount[/code].
				[codeblock]
				# a = 59
				a = dectime(60, 10, 0.1))
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: deg2rad
methods.description:
Returns degrees converted to radians.
				[codeblock]
				# r is 3.141593
				r = deg2rad(180)
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: dict2inst
methods.description: Converts a previously converted instance to a dictionary, back into an instance. Useful for deserializing.

methods.name: ease
methods.description: Easing function, based on exponent. 0 is constant, 1 is linear, 0 to 1 is ease-in, 1+ is ease out. Negative values are in-out/out in.

methods.name: exp
methods.description:
Raises the Euler's constant [b]e[/b] to the power of [code]s[/code] and returns it. [b]e[/b] has an approximate value of 2.71828.
				[codeblock]
				a = exp(2) # approximately 7.39
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: floor
methods.description:
Rounds [code]s[/code] to the closest smaller integer and returns it.
				[codeblock]
				# a is 2
				a = floor(2.99)
				# a is -3
				a = floor(-2.99)
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: fmod
methods.description:
Returns the floating-point remainder of [code]x/y[/code].
				[codeblock]
				# remainder is 1.5
				var remainder = fmod(7, 5.5)
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: fposmod
methods.description:
Returns the floating-point remainder of [code]x/y[/code] that wraps equally in positive and negative.
				[codeblock]
				var i = -10;
				while i < 0:
				    prints(i, fposmod(i, 10))
				    i += 1
				[/codeblock]
				Produces:
				[codeblock]
				-10 10
				-9 1
				-8 2
				-7 3
				-6 4
				-5 5
				-4 6
				-3 7
				-2 8
				-1 9
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: funcref
methods.description:
Returns a reference to the specified function [code]funcname[/code] in the [code]instance[/code] node. As functions aren't first-class objects in GDscript, use [code]funcref[/code] to store a [FuncRef] in a variable and call it later.
				[codeblock]
				func foo():
				    return("bar")

				a = funcref(self, "foo")
				print(a.call_func()) # prints bar
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: hash
methods.description:
Returns the integer hash of the variable passed.
				[codeblock]
				print(hash("a")) # prints 177670
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: inst2dict
methods.description:
Returns the passed instance converted to a dictionary (useful for serializing).
				[codeblock]
				var foo = "bar"
				func _ready():
				    var d = inst2dict(self)
				    print(d.keys())
				    print(d.values())
				[/codeblock]
				Prints out:
				[codeblock]
				[@subpath, @path, foo]
				[, res://test.gd, bar]
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: instance_from_id
inverse_lerp
methods.description:
Returns a normalized value considering the given range.
				[codeblock]
				inverse_lerp(3, 5, 4) # returns 0.5
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: is_inf
methods.description: Returns True/False whether [code]s[/code] is an infinity value (either positive infinity or negative infinity).

methods.name: is_nan
methods.description: Returns True/False whether [code]s[/code] is a NaN (Not-A-Number) value.

methods.name: len
methods.description:
Returns length of Variant [code]var[/code]. Length is the character count of String, element count of Array, size of Dictionary, etc. Note: Generates a fatal error if Variant can not provide a length.
				[codeblock]
				a = [1, 2, 3, 4]
				len(a) # returns 4
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: lerp
methods.description:
Linearly interpolates between two values by a normalized value.
				[codeblock]
				lerp(1, 3, 0.5) # returns 2
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: linear2db
methods.description: Converts from linear energy to decibels (audio).

methods.name: load
methods.description:
Loads a resource from the filesystem located at [code]path[/code]. Note: resource paths can be obtained by right clicking on a resource in the Assets Panel and choosing "Copy Path".
				[codeblock]
				# load a scene called main located in the root of the project directory
				var main = load("res://main.tscn")
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: log
methods.description:
Natural logarithm. The amount of time needed to reach a certain level of continuous growth. Note: This is not the same as the log function on your calculator which is a base 10 logarithm.
				[codeblock]
				log(10) # returns 2.302585
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: max
methods.description:
Returns the maximum of two values.
				[codeblock]
				max(1,2) # returns 2
				max(-3.99, -4) # returns -3.99
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: min
methods.description:
Returns the minimum of two values.
				[codeblock]
				min(1,2) # returns 1
				min(-3.99, -4) # returns -4
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: nearest_po2
methods.description:
Returns the nearest larger power of 2 for integer [code]value[/code].
				[codeblock]
				nearest_po2(3) # returns 4
				nearest_po2(4) # returns 4
				nearest_po2(5) # returns 8
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: parse_json
methods.description:
Parse JSON text to a Variant (use [method typeof] to check if it is what you expect).
				Be aware that the JSON specification does not define integer or float types, but only a number type. Therefore, parsing a JSON text will convert all numerical values to [float] types.
				[codeblock]
				p = parse_json('["a", "b", "c"]')
				if typeof(p) == TYPE_ARRAY:
				    print(p[0]) # prints a
				else:
				    print("unexpected results")
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: polar2cartesian
methods.description: Converts a 2D point expressed in the polar coordinate system (a distance from the origin [code]r[/code] and an angle [code]th[/code]) to the cartesian coordinate system (x and y axis).

methods.name: pow
methods.description:
Returns the result of [code]x[/code] raised to the power of [code]y[/code].
				[codeblock]
				pow(2,5) # returns 32
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: preload
methods.description:
Returns a resource from the filesystem that is loaded during script parsing. Note: resource paths can be obtained by right clicking on a resource in the Assets Panel and choosing "Copy Path".
				[codeblock]
				# load a scene called main located in the root of the project directory
				var main = preload("res://main.tscn")
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: print
methods.description:
Converts one or more arguments to strings in the best way possible and prints them to the console.
				[codeblock]
				a = [1,2,3]
				print("a","b",a) # prints ab[1, 2, 3]
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: print_stack
methods.description:
Prints a stack track at code location, only works when running with debugger turned on.
				Output in the console would look something like this:
				[codeblock]
				Frame 0 - res://test.gd:16 in function '_process'
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: printerr
methods.description:
Prints one or more arguments to strings in the best way possible to standard error line.
				[codeblock]
				printerr("prints to stderr")
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: printraw
methods.description:
Prints one or more arguments to strings in the best way possible to console. No newline is added at the end.
				[codeblock]
				printraw("A")
				printraw("B")
				# prints AB
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: prints
methods.description:
Prints one or more arguments to the console with a space between each argument.
				[codeblock]
				prints("A", "B", "C") # prints A B C
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: printt
methods.description:
Prints one or more arguments to the console with a tab between each argument.
				[codeblock]
				printt("A", "B", "C") # prints A       B       C
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: rad2deg
methods.description:
Converts from radians to degrees.
				[codeblock]
				rad2deg(0.523599) # returns 30
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: rand_range
methods.description:
Random range, any floating point value between [code]from[/code] and [code]to[/code].
				[codeblock]
				prints(rand_range(0, 1), rand_range(0, 1)) # prints 0.135591 0.405263
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: rand_seed
methods.description: Random from seed: pass a [code]seed[/code], and an array with both number and new seed is returned. "Seed" here refers to the internal state of the pseudo random number generator. The internal state of the current implementation is 64 bits.

methods.name: randf
methods.description:
Returns a random floating point value between 0 and 1.
				[codeblock]
				randf() # returns 0.375671
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: randi
methods.description:
Returns a random 32 bit integer. Use remainder to obtain a random value between 0 and N (where N is smaller than 2^32 -1).
				[codeblock]
				randi() % 20      # returns random number between 0 and 19
				randi() % 100     # returns random number between 0 and 99
				randi() % 100 + 1 # returns random number between 1 and 100
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: randomize
methods.description:
Randomizes the seed (or the internal state) of the random number generator. Current implementation reseeds using a number based on time.
				[codeblock]
				func _ready():
				    randomize()
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: range
methods.description:
Returns an array with the given range. Range can be 1 argument N (0 to N-1), two arguments (initial, final-1) or three arguments (initial, final-1, increment).
				[codeblock]
				for i in range(4):
				    print(i)
				for i in range(2, 5):
				    print(i)
				for i in range(0, 6, 2):
				    print(i)
				[/codeblock]
				Output:
				[codeblock]
				0
				1
				2
				3

				2
				3
				4

				0
				2
				4
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: range_lerp
methods.description:
Maps a [code]value[/code] from range [code][istart, istop][/code] to [code][ostart, ostop][/code].
				[codeblock]
				range_lerp(75, 0, 100, -1, 1) # returns 0.5
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: round
methods.description:
Returns the integral value that is nearest to [code]s[/code], with halfway cases rounded away from zero.
				[codeblock]
				round(2.6) # returns 3
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: seed
methods.description:
Sets seed for the random number generator.
				[codeblock]
				my_seed = "Godot Rocks"
				seed(my_seed.hash())
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: sign
methods.description:
Returns the sign of [code]s[/code]: -1 or 1. Returns 0 if [code]s[/code] is 0.
				[codeblock]
				sign(-6) # returns -1
				sign(0)  # returns 0
				sign(6)  # returns 1
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: sin
methods.description:
Returns the sine of angle [code]s[/code] in radians.
				[codeblock]
				sin(0.523599) # returns 0.5
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: sinh
methods.description:
Returns the hyperbolic sine of [code]s[/code].
				[codeblock]
				a = log(2.0) # returns 0.693147
				sinh(a) # returns 0.75
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: sqrt
methods.description:
Returns the square root of [code]s[/code].
				[codeblock]
				sqrt(9) # returns 3
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: stepify
methods.description: Snaps float value [code]s[/code] to a given [code]step[/code].

methods.name: str
methods.description:
Converts one or more arguments to string in the best way possible.
				[codeblock]
				var a = [10, 20, 30]
				var b = str(a);
				len(a) # returns 3
				len(b) # returns 12
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: str2var
methods.description:
Converts a formatted string that was returned by [method var2str] to the original value.
				[codeblock]
				a = '{ "a": 1, "b": 2 }'
				b = str2var(a)
				print(b['a']) # prints 1
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: tan
methods.description:
Returns the tangent of angle [code]s[/code] in radians.
				[codeblock]
				tan( deg2rad(45) ) # returns 1
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: tanh
methods.description:
Returns the hyperbolic tangent of [code]s[/code].
				[codeblock]
				a = log(2.0) # returns 0.693147
				tanh(a)      # returns 0.6
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: to_json
type_exists
methods.description:
Returns whether the given class exists in [ClassDB].
				[codeblock]
				type_exists("Sprite") # returns true
				type_exists("Variant") # returns false
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: typeof
methods.description:
Returns the internal type of the given Variant object, using the TYPE_* enum in [@GlobalScope].
				[codeblock]
				p = parse_json('["a", "b", "c"]')
				if typeof(p) == TYPE_ARRAY:
				    print(p[0]) # prints a
				else:
				    print("unexpected results")
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: validate_json
methods.description:
Checks that [code]json[/code] is valid JSON data. Returns empty string if valid. Returns error message if not valid.
				[codeblock]
				j = to_json([1, 2, 3])
				v = validate_json(j)
				if not v:
				    print("valid")
				else:
				    prints("invalid", v)
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: var2bytes
methods.description: Encodes a variable value to a byte array.

methods.name: var2str
methods.description:
Converts a Variant [code]var[/code] to a formatted string that can later be parsed using [method str2var].
				[codeblock]
				a = { 'a': 1, 'b': 2 }
				print(var2str(a))
				[/codeblock]
				prints
				[codeblock]
				{
				"a": 1,
				"b": 2
				}
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: weakref
methods.description:
Returns a weak reference to an object.
				A weak reference to an object is not enough to keep the object alive: when the only remaining references to a referent are weak references, garbage collection is free to destroy the referent and reuse its memory for something else. However, until the object is actually destroyed the weak reference may return the object even if there are no strong references to it.

methods.name: wrapf
methods.description:
Wraps float [code]value[/code] between [code]min[/code] and [code]max[/code].
				Usable for creating loop-alike behavior or infinite surfaces.
				[codeblock]
				# a is 0.5
				a = wrapf(10.5, 0.0, 10.0)
				[/codeblock]
				[codeblock]
				# a is 9.5
				a = wrapf(-0.5, 0.0, 10.0)
				[/codeblock]
				[codeblock]
				# infinite loop between 0.0 and 0.99
				f = wrapf(f + 0.1, 0.0, 1.0)
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: wrapi
methods.description:
Wraps integer [code]value[/code] between [code]min[/code] and [code]max[/code].
				Usable for creating loop-alike behavior or infinite surfaces.
				[codeblock]
				# a is 0
				a = wrapi(10, 0, 10)
				[/codeblock]
				[codeblock]
				# a is 9
				a = wrapi(-1, 0, 10)
				[/codeblock]
				[codeblock]
				# infinite loop between 0 and 9
				frame = wrapi(frame + 1, 0, 10)
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: yield
methods.description:
Stops the function execution and returns the current state. Call [method GDScriptFunctionState.resume] on the state to resume execution. This invalidates the state.
				Returns anything that was passed to the resume function call. If passed an object and a signal, the execution is resumed when the object's signal is emitted.

constants.name: PI
constants.description: Constant that represents how many times the diameter of a circle fits around its perimeter.

constants.name: TAU
constants.description: The circle constant, the circumference of the unit circle.

constants.name: INF
constants.description: A positive infinity. (For negative infinity, use -INF).

constants.name: NAN
constants.description:
Macro constant that expands to an expression of type float that represents a NaN.
			The NaN values are used to identify undefined or non-representable values for floating-point elements, such as the square root of negative numbers or the result of 0/0.

CanvasLayer.name: CanvasLayer
CanvasLayer.description: Canvas drawing layer. [CanvasItem] nodes that are direct or indirect children of a [code]CanvasLayer[/code] will be drawn in that layer. The layer is a numeric index that defines the draw order. The default 2D scene renders with index 0, so a [code]CanvasLayer[/code] with index -1 will be drawn below, and one with index 1 will be drawn above. This is very useful for HUDs (in layer 1+ or above), or backgrounds (in layer -1 or below).

methods.name: get_world_2d
methods.description: Return the [World2D] used by this layer.

properties.name: custom_viewport
properties.description: The custom [Viewport] node assigned to the [code]CanvasLayer[/code]. If null, uses the default viewport instead.

properties.name: layer
properties.description: Layer index for draw order. Lower values are drawn first. Default value: [code]1[/code].

properties.name: offset
properties.description: The layer's base offset.

properties.name: rotation
properties.description: The layer's rotation in radians.

properties.name: rotation_degrees
properties.description: The layer's rotation in degrees.

properties.name: scale
properties.description: The layer's scale.

properties.name: transform
properties.description: The layer's transform.

AudioEffectPitchShift.name: AudioEffectPitchShift
AudioEffectPitchShift.brief_description:
Adds a Pitch shift audio effect to an Audio bus.
		Raises or lowers the pitch of original sound.
AudioEffectPitchShift.description: Allows modulation of pitch independently of tempo. All frequencies can be increased/decreased with minimal effect on transients.

properties.name: pitch_scale
properties.description: Pitch value. Can range from 0 (-1 octave) to 16 (+16 octaves).

AudioEffectReverb.name: AudioEffectReverb
AudioEffectReverb.brief_description:
Adds a Reverb audio effect to an Audio bus.
		Simulates the sound of acoustic environments such as rooms, concert halls, caverns, or an open spaces.
AudioEffectReverb.description: Simulates rooms of different sizes. Its parameters can be adjusted to simulate the sound of a specific room.

properties.name: damping
properties.description: Widens or narrows the stereo image of the reverb tail. 1 means fully widens. Value can range from 0 to 1. Default value: [code]1[/code].

properties.name: dry
properties.description: Output percent of original sound. At 0, only modified sound is outputted. Value can range from 0 to 1. Default value: [code]1[/code].

properties.name: hipass
properties.description: High-pass filter passes signals with a frequency higher than a certain cutoff frequency and attenuates signals with frequencies lower than the cutoff frequency. Value can range from 0 to 1. Default value: [code]0[/code].

properties.name: predelay_feedback
properties.description: Output percent of predelay. Value can range from 0 to 1. Default value: [code]1[/code].

properties.name: predelay_msec
properties.description: Time between the original signal and the early reflections of the reverb signal. Default value: [code]150ms[/code].

properties.name: room_size
properties.description: Dimensions of simulated room. Bigger means more echoes. Value can range from 0 to 1. Default value: [code]0.8[/code].

properties.name: spread
properties.description: Defines how reflective the imaginary room's walls are. Value can range from 0 to 1. Default value: [code]1[/code].

properties.name: wet
properties.description: Output percent of modified sound. At 0, only original sound is outputted. Value can range from 0 to 1. Default value: [code]0.5[/code].

VisualScriptReturn.name: VisualScriptReturn
VisualScriptReturn.brief_description: Exits a function and returns an optional value.
VisualScriptReturn.description:
Ends the execution of a function and returns control to the calling function. Optionally, it can return a [Variant] value.
		[b]Input Ports:[/b]
		- Sequence
		- Data (variant): [code]result[/code] (optional)
		[b]Output Ports:[/b]
		none

properties.name: return_enabled
properties.description: If [code]true[/code] the [code]return[/code] input port is available.

properties.name: return_type
properties.description: The return value's data type.

TileSet.name: TileSet
TileSet.description:
A TileSet is a library of tiles for a [TileMap]. It contains a list of tiles, each consisting of a sprite and optional collision shapes.
		Tiles are referenced by a unique integer ID.

methods.name: clear
methods.description: Clear all tiles.

methods.name: create_tile
methods.description: Create a new tile which will be referenced by the given ID.

methods.name: find_tile_by_name
methods.description: Find the first tile matching the given name.

methods.name: get_last_unused_tile_id
methods.description: Return the ID following the last currently used ID, useful when creating a new tile.

methods.name: get_tiles_ids
methods.description: Return an array of all currently used tile IDs.

methods.name: remove_tile
methods.description: Remove the tile referenced by the given ID.

methods.name: tile_get_light_occluder
methods.description: Return the light occluder of the tile.

methods.name: tile_get_material
methods.description: Return the material of the tile.

methods.name: tile_get_name
methods.description: Return the name of the tile.

methods.name: tile_get_navigation_polygon
methods.description: Return the navigation polygon of the tile.

methods.name: tile_get_navigation_polygon_offset
methods.description: Return the offset of the tile's navigation polygon.

methods.name: tile_get_occluder_offset
methods.description: Return the offset of the tile's light occluder.

methods.name: tile_get_region
methods.description: Return the tile sub-region in the texture.

methods.name: tile_get_shapes
methods.description: Return the array of shapes of the tile.

methods.name: tile_get_texture
methods.description: Return the texture of the tile.

methods.name: tile_get_texture_offset
methods.description: Return the texture offset of the tile.

methods.name: tile_set_light_occluder
methods.description: Set a light occluder for the tile.

methods.name: tile_set_material
methods.description: Set the material of the tile.

methods.name: tile_set_name
methods.description: Set the name of the tile, for descriptive purposes.

methods.name: tile_set_navigation_polygon
methods.description: Set a navigation polygon for the tile.

methods.name: tile_set_navigation_polygon_offset
methods.description: Set an offset for the tile's navigation polygon.

methods.name: tile_set_occluder_offset
methods.description: Set an offset for the tile's light occluder.

methods.name: tile_set_region
methods.description: Set the tile sub-region in the texture. This is common in texture atlases.

methods.name: tile_set_shapes
methods.description: Set an array of shapes for the tile, enabling physics to collide with it.

methods.name: tile_set_texture
methods.description: Set the texture of the tile.

methods.name: tile_set_texture_offset
methods.description: Set the texture offset of the tile.

Node.name: Node
Node.description:
Nodes are Godot's building blocks. They can be assigned as the child of another node, resulting in a tree arrangement. A given node can contain any number of nodes as children with the requirement that all siblings (direct children of a node) should have unique names.
		A tree of nodes is called a [i]scene[/i]. Scenes can be saved to the disk and then instanced into other scenes. This allows for very high flexibility in the architecture and data model of Godot projects. Nodes can also optionally be added to groups. This makes it possible to access a number of nodes from code (an "enemies" group, for example) to perform grouped actions.
		[b]Scene tree:[/b] The [SceneTree] contains the active tree of nodes. When a node is added to the scene tree, it receives the NOTIFICATION_ENTER_TREE notification and its [method _enter_tree] callback is triggered. Child nodes are always added [i]after[/i] their parent node, i.e. the [method _enter_tree] callback of a parent node will be triggered before its child's.
		Once all nodes have been added in the scene tree, they receive the NOTIFICATION_READY notification and their respective [method _ready] callbacks are triggered. For groups of nodes, the [method _ready] callback is called in reverse order, starting with the children and moving up to the parent nodes.
		This means that when adding a node to the scene tree, the following order will be used for the callbacks: [method _enter_tree] of the parent, [method _enter_tree] of the children, [method _ready] of the children and finally [method _ready] of the parent (recursively for the entire scene tree).
		[b]Processing:[/b] Nodes can override the "process" state, so that they receive a callback on each frame requesting them to process (do something). Normal processing (callback [method _process], toggled with [method set_process]) happens as fast as possible and is dependent on the frame rate, so the processing time [i]delta[/i] is passed as an argument. Physics processing (callback [method _physics_process], toggled with [method set_physics_process]) happens a fixed number of times per second (60 by default) and is useful for code related to the physics engine.
		Nodes can also process input events. When present, the [method _input] function will be called for each input that the program receives. In many cases, this can be overkill (unless used for simple projects), and the [method _unhandled_input] function might be preferred; it is called when the input event was not handled by anyone else (typically, GUI [Control] nodes), ensuring that the node only receives the events that were meant for it.
		To keep track of the scene hierarchy (especially when instancing scenes into other scenes), an "owner" can be set for the node with [method set_owner]. This keeps track of who instanced what. This is mostly useful when writing editors and tools, though.
		Finally, when a node is freed with [method free] or [method queue_free], it will also free all its children.
		[b]Networking with nodes:[/b] After connecting to a server (or making one, see [NetworkedMultiplayerENet]) it is possible to use the built-in RPC (remote procedure call) system to communicate over the network. By calling [method rpc] with a method name, it will be called locally and in all connected peers (peers = clients and the server that accepts connections), with behaviour varying depending on the network mode ([method set_network_mode]) of the receiving peer. To identify which node receives the RPC call Godot will use its [NodePath] (make sure node names are the same on all peers).

methods.name: _enter_tree
methods.description:
Called when the node enters the [SceneTree] (e.g. upon instancing, scene changing, or after calling [method add_child] in a script). If the node has children, its [method _enter_tree] callback will be called first, and then that of the children.
				Corresponds to the NOTIFICATION_ENTER_TREE notification in [method Object._notification].

methods.name: _exit_tree
methods.description:
Called when the node is about to leave the [SceneTree] (e.g. upon freeing, scene changing, or after calling [method remove_child] in a script). If the node has children, its [method _exit_tree] callback will be called last, after all its children have left the tree.
				Corresponds to the NOTIFICATION_EXIT_TREE notification in [method Object._notification] and signal [signal tree_exiting]. To get notified when the node has already left the active tree, connect to the [signal tree_exited]

methods.name: _input
methods.description:
Called when there is an input event. The input event propagates through the node tree until a node consumes it.
				It is only called if input processing is enabled, which is done automatically if this method is overridden, and can be toggled with [method set_process_input].

methods.name: _physics_process
methods.description:
Called during the physics processing step of the main loop. Physics processing means that the frame rate is synced to the physics, i.e. the [code]delta[/code] variable should be constant.
				It is only called if physics processing is enabled, which is done automatically if this method is overridden, and can be toggled with [method set_physics_process].
				Corresponds to the NOTIFICATION_PHYSICS_PROCESS notification in [method Object._notification].

methods.name: _process
methods.description:
Called during the processing step of the main loop. Processing happens at every frame and as fast as possible, so the [code]delta[/code] time since the previous frame is not constant.
				It is only called if processing is enabled, which is done automatically if this method is overridden, and can be toggled with [method set_process].
				Corresponds to the NOTIFICATION_PROCESS notification in [method Object._notification].

methods.name: _ready
methods.description:
Called when the node is "ready", i.e. when both the node and its children have entered the scene tree. If the node has children, their [method _ready] callbacks get triggered first, and the parent node will receive the ready notification afterwards.
				Corresponds to the NOTIFICATION_READY notification in [method Object._notification].

methods.name: _unhandled_input
methods.description:
Propagated to all nodes when the previous InputEvent is not consumed by any nodes.
				It is only called if unhandled input processing is enabled, which is done automatically if this method is overridden, and can be toggled with [method set_process_unhandled_input].

methods.name: add_child
methods.description:
Adds a child node. Nodes can have any number of children, but every child must have a unique name. Child nodes are automatically deleted when the parent node is deleted, so an entire scene can be removed by deleting its topmost node.
				Setting "legible_unique_name" [code]true[/code] creates child nodes with human-readable names, based on the name of the node being instanced instead of its type.

methods.name: add_child_below_node
methods.description:
Adds a child node. The child is placed below the given node in the list of children.
				Setting "legible_unique_name" [code]true[/code] creates child nodes with human-readable names, based on the name of the node being instanced instead of its type.

methods.name: add_to_group
methods.description: Adds the node to a group. Groups are helpers to name and organize a subset of nodes, for example "enemies" or "collectables". A node can be in any number of groups. Nodes can be assigned a group at any time, but will not be added until they are inside the scene tree (see [method is_inside_tree]).

methods.name: can_process
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if the node can process while the scene tree is paused (see [method set_pause_mode]). Always returns [code]true[/code] if the scene tree is not paused, and [code]false[/code] if the node is not in the tree. FIXME: Why FAIL_COND?

methods.name: duplicate
methods.description:
Duplicates the node, returning a new node.
				You can fine-tune the behavior using the [code]flags[/code]. See DUPLICATE_* constants.

methods.name: find_node
methods.description: Finds a descendant of this node whose name matches [code]mask[/code] as in [method String.match] (i.e. case sensitive, but '*' matches zero or more characters and '?' matches any single character except '.'). Note that it does not match against the full path, just against individual node names.

methods.name: get_child
methods.description: Returns a child node by its index (see [method get_child_count]). This method is often used for iterating all children of a node.

methods.name: get_child_count
methods.description: Returns the number of child nodes.

methods.name: get_children
methods.description: Returns an array of references to node's children.

methods.name: get_groups
methods.description: Returns an array listing the groups that the node is a member of.

methods.name: get_index
methods.description: Returns the node's index, i.e. its position among the siblings of its parent.

methods.name: get_network_master
methods.description: Returns the peer ID of the network master for this node.

methods.name: get_node
methods.description:
Fetches a node. The [NodePath] can be either a relative path (from the current node) or an absolute path (in the scene tree) to a node. If the path does not exist, a [code]null instance[/code] is returned and attempts to access it will result in an "Attempt to call <method> on a null instance." error.
				Note: fetching absolute paths only works when the node is inside the scene tree (see [method is_inside_tree]).
				[i]Example:[/i] Assume your current node is Character and the following tree:
				[codeblock]
				/root
				/root/Character
				/root/Character/Sword
				/root/Character/Backpack/Dagger
				/root/MyGame
				/root/Swamp/Alligator
				/root/Swamp/Mosquito
				/root/Swamp/Goblin
				[/codeblock]
				Possible paths are:
				[codeblock]
				get_node("Sword")
				get_node("Backpack/Dagger")
				get_node("../Swamp/Alligator")
				get_node("/root/MyGame")
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: get_parent
methods.description: Returns the parent node of the current node, or an empty [code]Node[/code] if the node lacks a parent.

methods.name: get_path
methods.description: Returns the absolute path of the current node. This only works if the current node is inside the scene tree (see [method is_inside_tree]).

methods.name: get_path_to
methods.description: Returns the relative path from the current node to the specified node in "node" argument. Both nodes must be in the same scene, or the function will fail.

methods.name: get_physics_process_delta_time
methods.description: Returns the time elapsed since the last physics-bound frame (see [method _physics_process]). This is always a constant value in physics processing unless the frames per second is changed in [OS].

methods.name: get_position_in_parent
methods.description: Returns the node's order in the scene tree branch. For example, if called on the first child node the position is [code]0[/code].

methods.name: get_process_delta_time
methods.description: Returns the time elapsed (in seconds) since the last process callback. This value may vary from frame to frame.

methods.name: get_tree
methods.description: Returns the [SceneTree] that contains this node.

methods.name: get_viewport
methods.description: Returns the node's [Viewport].

methods.name: has_node
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if the node that the [NodePath] points to exists.

methods.name: is_a_parent_of
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if the given node is a direct or indirect child of the current node.

methods.name: is_displayed_folded
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if the node is folded (collapsed) in the Scene dock.

methods.name: is_greater_than
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if the given node occurs later in the scene hierarchy than the current node.

methods.name: is_in_group
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if this node is in the specified group.

methods.name: is_inside_tree
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if this node is currently inside a [SceneTree].

methods.name: is_physics_processing
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if physics processing is enabled (see [method set_physics_process]).

methods.name: is_processing
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if processing is enabled (see [method set_process]).

methods.name: is_processing_input
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if the node is processing input (see [method set_process_input]).

methods.name: is_processing_unhandled_input
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if the node is processing unhandled input (see [method set_process_unhandled_input]).

methods.name: is_processing_unhandled_key_input
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if the node is processing unhandled key input (see [method set_process_unhandled_key_input]).

methods.name: move_child
methods.description: Moves a child node to a different position (order) amongst the other children. Since calls, signals, etc are performed by tree order, changing the order of children nodes may be useful.

methods.name: print_tree
methods.description: Prints the scene to stdout. Used mainly for debugging purposes.

methods.name: propagate_call
methods.description: Calls the given method (if present) with the arguments given in [code]args[/code] on this node and recursively on all its children. If the parent_first argument is [code]true[/code] then the method will be called on the current node first, then on all children. If it is [code]false[/code] then the children will be called first.

methods.name: propagate_notification
methods.description: Notifies the current node and all its children recursively by calling notification() on all of them.

methods.name: queue_free
methods.description: Queues a node for deletion at the end of the current frame. When deleted, all of its child nodes will be deleted as well. This method ensures it's safe to delete the node, contrary to [method Object.free]. Use [method Object.is_queued_for_deletion] to check whether a node will be deleted at the end of the frame.

methods.name: raise
methods.description: Moves this node to the top of the array of nodes of the parent node. This is often useful in GUIs ([Control] nodes), because their order of drawing depends on their order in the tree.

methods.name: remove_and_skip
methods.description: Removes a node and sets all its children as children of the parent node (if it exists). All event subscriptions that pass by the removed node will be unsubscribed.

methods.name: remove_child
methods.description: Removes a child node. The node is NOT deleted and must be deleted manually.

methods.name: remove_from_group
methods.description: Removes a node from a group.

methods.name: replace_by
methods.description: Replaces a node in a scene by the given one. Subscriptions that pass through this node will be lost.

methods.name: request_ready
methods.description: Requests that [code]_ready[/code] be called again.

methods.name: rpc
methods.description: Sends a remote procedure call request to all peers on the network (and locally), optionally sending additional data as arguments. Call request will be received by nodes with the same [NodePath].

methods.name: rpc_config
