methods.description: Changes the method's RPC mode (one of RPC_MODE_* constants).

methods.name: rpc_id
methods.description: Sends a [method rpc] to a specific peer identified by [i]peer_id[/i].

methods.name: rpc_unreliable
methods.description: Sends a [method rpc] using an unreliable protocol.

methods.name: rpc_unreliable_id
methods.description: Sends a [method rpc] to a specific peer identified by [i]peer_id[/i] using an unreliable protocol.

methods.name: rset
methods.description: Remotely changes property's value on other peers (and locally).

methods.name: rset_config
methods.description: Changes the property's RPC mode (one of RPC_MODE_* constants).

methods.name: rset_id
methods.description: Remotely changes property's value on a specific peer identified by [i]peer_id[/i].

methods.name: rset_unreliable
methods.description: Remotely changes property's value on other peers (and locally) using an unreliable protocol.

methods.name: rset_unreliable_id
methods.description: Remotely changes property's value on a specific peer identified by [i]peer_id[/i] using an unreliable protocol.

methods.name: set_display_folded
methods.description: Sets the folded state of the node in the Scene dock.

methods.name: set_network_master
methods.description: Sets the node network master to the peer with the given peer ID. The network master is the peer that has authority over it on the network. Inherited from the parent node by default, which ultimately defaults to peer ID 1 (the server).

methods.name: set_physics_process
methods.description: Enables or disables physics (i.e. fixed framerate) processing. When a node is being processed, it will receive a NOTIFICATION_PHYSICS_PROCESS at a fixed (usually 60 fps, see [OS] to change) interval (and the [method _physics_process] callback will be called if exists). Enabled automatically if [method _physics_process] is overridden. Any calls to this before [method _ready] will be ignored.

methods.name: set_process
methods.description: Enables or disables processing. When a node is being processed, it will receive a NOTIFICATION_PROCESS on every drawn frame (and the [method _process] callback will be called if exists). Enabled automatically if [method _process] is overridden. Any calls to this before [method _ready] will be ignored.

methods.name: set_process_input
methods.description: Enables or disables input processing. This is not required for GUI controls! Enabled automatically if [method _input] is overridden. Any calls to this before [method _ready] will be ignored.

methods.name: set_process_unhandled_input
methods.description: Enables unhandled input processing. This is not required for GUI controls! It enables the node to receive all input that was not previously handled (usually by a [Control]). Enabled automatically if [method _unhandled_input] is overridden. Any calls to this before [method _ready] will be ignored.

methods.name: set_process_unhandled_key_input
methods.description: Enables unhandled key input processing. Enabled automatically if [method _unhandled_key_input] is overridden. Any calls to this before [method _ready] will be ignored.

signals.name: renamed
signals.description: Emitted when the node is renamed.

signals.name: tree_entered
signals.description: Emitted when the node enters the tree.

signals.name: tree_exited
signals.description: Emitted after the node exits the tree and is no longer active.

signals.name: tree_exiting
signals.description: Emitted when the node is still active but about to exit the tree. This is the right place for de-initialization.

constants.name: NOTIFICATION_ENTER_TREE
constants.description: Notification received when the node enters a [SceneTree].

constants.name: NOTIFICATION_EXIT_TREE
constants.description: Notification received when the node is about to exit a [SceneTree].

constants.name: NOTIFICATION_MOVED_IN_PARENT
constants.description: Notification received when the node is moved in the parent.

constants.name: NOTIFICATION_READY
constants.description: Notification received when the node is ready. See [method _ready].

constants.name: NOTIFICATION_PAUSED
constants.description: Notification received when the node is paused.

constants.name: NOTIFICATION_UNPAUSED
constants.description: Notification received when the node is unpaused.

constants.name: NOTIFICATION_PHYSICS_PROCESS
constants.description: Notification received every frame when the physics process flag is set (see [method set_physics_process]).

constants.name: NOTIFICATION_PROCESS
constants.description: Notification received every frame when the process flag is set (see [method set_process]).

constants.name: NOTIFICATION_PARENTED
constants.description: Notification received when a node is set as a child of another node. Note that this doesn't mean that a node entered the Scene Tree.

constants.name: NOTIFICATION_UNPARENTED
constants.description: Notification received when a node is unparented (parent removed it from the list of children).

constants.name: NOTIFICATION_INSTANCED
constants.description: Notification received when the node is instanced.

constants.name: NOTIFICATION_DRAG_BEGIN
constants.description: Notification received when a drag begins.

constants.name: NOTIFICATION_DRAG_END
constants.description: Notification received when a drag ends.

constants.name: NOTIFICATION_PATH_CHANGED
constants.description: Notification received when the node's [NodePath] changed.

constants.name: RPC_MODE_REMOTE
constants.description: Call a method remotely.

constants.name: RPC_MODE_SYNC
constants.description: Call a method both remotely and locally.

constants.name: RPC_MODE_MASTER
constants.description: Call a method if the Node is Master.

constants.name: RPC_MODE_SLAVE
constants.description: Call a method if the Node is Slave.

constants.name: PAUSE_MODE_INHERIT
constants.description: Inherits pause mode from parent. For root node, it is equivalent to PAUSE_MODE_STOP.

constants.name: PAUSE_MODE_STOP
constants.description: Stop processing when SceneTree is paused.

constants.name: PAUSE_MODE_PROCESS
constants.description: Continue to process regardless of SceneTree pause state.

constants.name: DUPLICATE_SIGNALS
constants.description: Duplicate the node's signals.

constants.name: DUPLICATE_GROUPS
constants.description: Duplicate the node's groups.

constants.name: DUPLICATE_SCRIPTS
constants.description: Duplicate the node's scripts.

constants.name: DUPLICATE_USE_INSTANCING
constants.description: Duplicate using instancing.

properties.name: filename
properties.description: When a scene is instanced from a file, its topmost node contains the filename from which it was loaded.

properties.name: name
properties.description:
The name of the node. This name is unique among the siblings (other child nodes from the same parent).
			When set to an existing name, the node will be automatically renamed

properties.name: owner
properties.description: The node owner. A node can have any other node as owner (as long as it is a valid parent, grandparent, etc. ascending in the tree). When saving a node (using SceneSaver) all the nodes it owns will be saved with it. This allows for the creation of complex [SceneTree]s, with instancing and subinstancing.

VisualScript.name: VisualScript
VisualScript.brief_description: A script implemented in the Visual Script programming environment.
VisualScript.description:
A script implemented in the  Visual Script programming environment. The script extends the functionality of all objects that instance it.
		[method Object.set_script] extends an existing object, if that object's class matches one of the script's base classes.
		You are most likely to use this class via the Visual Script editor or when writing plugins for it.

methods.name: add_custom_signal
methods.description: Add a custom signal with the specified name to the VisualScript.

methods.name: add_function
methods.description: Add a function with the specified name to the VisualScript.

methods.name: add_node
methods.description: Add a node to a function of the VisualScript.

methods.name: add_variable
methods.description: Add a variable to the VisualScript, optionally giving it a default value or marking it as exported.

methods.name: custom_signal_add_argument
methods.description: Add an argument to a custom signal added with [method add_custom_signal].

methods.name: custom_signal_get_argument_count
methods.description: Get the count of a custom signal's arguments.

methods.name: custom_signal_get_argument_name
methods.description: Get the name of a custom signal's argument.

methods.name: custom_signal_get_argument_type
methods.description: Get the type of a custom signal's argument.

methods.name: custom_signal_remove_argument
methods.description: Remove a specific custom signal's argument.

methods.name: custom_signal_set_argument_name
methods.description: Rename a custom signal's argument.

methods.name: custom_signal_set_argument_type
methods.description: Change the type of a custom signal's argument.

methods.name: custom_signal_swap_argument
methods.description: Swap two of the arguments of a custom signal.

methods.name: data_connect
methods.description: Connect two data ports. The value of [code]from_node[/code]'s [code]from_port[/code] would be fed into [code]to_node[/code]'s [code]to_port[/code].

methods.name: data_disconnect
methods.description: Disconnect two data ports previously connected with [method data_connect].

methods.name: get_function_node_id
methods.description: Returns the id of a function's entry point node.

methods.name: get_function_scroll
methods.description: Returns the position of the center of the screen for a given function.

methods.name: get_node
methods.description: Returns a node given its id and its function.

methods.name: get_node_position
methods.description: Returns a node's position in pixels.

methods.name: get_variable_default_value
methods.description: Returns the default (initial) value of a variable.

methods.name: get_variable_export
methods.description: Returns whether a variable is exported.

methods.name: get_variable_info
methods.description: Returns the info for a given variable as a dictionary. The information includes its name, type, hint and usage.

methods.name: has_custom_signal
methods.description: Returns whether a signal exists with the specified name.

methods.name: has_data_connection
methods.description: Returns whether the specified data ports are connected.

methods.name: has_function
methods.description: Returns whether a function exists with the specified name.

methods.name: has_node
methods.description: Returns whether a node exists with the given id.

methods.name: has_sequence_connection
methods.description: Returns whether the specified sequence ports are connected.

methods.name: has_variable
methods.description: Returns whether a variable exists with the specified name.

methods.name: remove_custom_signal
methods.description: Remove a custom signal with the given name.

methods.name: remove_function
methods.description: Remove a specific function and its nodes from the script.

methods.name: remove_node
methods.description: Remove a specific node.

methods.name: remove_variable
methods.description: Remove a variable with the given name.

methods.name: rename_custom_signal
methods.description: Change the name of a custom signal.

methods.name: rename_function
methods.description: Change the name of a function.

methods.name: rename_variable
methods.description: Change the name of a variable.

methods.name: sequence_connect
methods.description:
Connect two sequence ports. The execution will flow from of [code]from_node[/code]'s [code]from_output[/code] into [code]to_node[/code].
				Unlike [method data_connect], there isn't a [code]to_port[/code], since the target node can have only one sequence port.

methods.name: sequence_disconnect
methods.description: Disconnect two sequence ports previously connected with [method sequence_connect].

methods.name: set_function_scroll
methods.description: Position the center of the screen for a function.

methods.name: set_instance_base_type
methods.description: Set the base type of the script.

methods.name: set_node_position
methods.description: Position a node on the screen.

methods.name: set_variable_default_value
methods.description: Change the default (initial) value of a variable.

methods.name: set_variable_export
methods.description: Change whether a variable is exported.

methods.name: set_variable_info
methods.description: Set a variable's info, using the same format as [method get_variable_info].

signals.name: node_ports_changed
signals.description: Emitted when the ports of a node are changed.

HTTPClient.name: HTTPClient
HTTPClient.description:
Hyper-text transfer protocol client (sometimes called "User Agent"). Used to make HTTP requests to download web content, upload files and other data or to communicate with various services, among other use cases.
		Note that this client only needs to connect to a host once (see [method connect_to_host]) to send multiple requests. Because of this, methods that take URLs usually take just the part after the host instead of the full URL, as the client is already connected to a host. See [method request] for a full example and to get started.
		A [code]HTTPClient[/code] should be reused between multiple requests or to connect to different hosts instead of creating one client per request. Supports SSL and SSL server certificate verification. HTTP status codes in the 2xx range indicate success, 3xx redirection (i.e. "try again, but over here"), 4xx something was wrong with the request, and 5xx something went wrong on the server's side.
		For more information on HTTP, see https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP (or read RFC 2616 to get it straight from the source: https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2616).

methods.name: close
methods.description: Closes the current connection, allowing reuse of this [code]HTTPClient[/code].

methods.name: connect_to_host
methods.description:
Connect to a host. This needs to be done before any requests are sent.
				The host should not have http:// prepended but will strip the protocol identifier if provided.
				If no [code]port[/code] is specified (or [code]-1[/code] is used), it is automatically set to 80 for HTTP and 443 for HTTPS (if [code]use_ssl[/code] is enabled).
				[code]verify_host[/code] will check the SSL identity of the host if set to [code]true[/code].

methods.name: get_response_body_length
methods.description: Returns the response's body length.

methods.name: get_response_code
methods.description: Returns the response's HTTP status code.

methods.name: get_response_headers
methods.description: Returns the response headers.

methods.name: get_response_headers_as_dictionary
methods.description:
Returns all response headers as dictionary where the case-sensitivity of the keys and values is kept like the server delivers it. A value is a simple String, this string can have more than one value where "; " is used as separator.
				Structure: ("key":"value1; value2")
				Example: (content-length:12), (Content-Type:application/json; charset=UTF-8)

methods.name: get_status
methods.description: Returns a STATUS_* enum constant. Need to call [method poll] in order to get status updates.

methods.name: has_response
methods.description: If [code]true[/code] this [code]HTTPClient[/code] has a response available.

methods.name: is_response_chunked
methods.description: If [code]true[/code] this [code]HTTPClient[/code] has a response that is chunked.

methods.name: poll
methods.description: This needs to be called in order to have any request processed. Check results with [method get_status]

methods.name: query_string_from_dict
methods.description:
Generates a GET/POST application/x-www-form-urlencoded style query string from a provided dictionary, e.g.:
				[codeblock]
				var fields = {"username": "user", "password": "pass"}
				String queryString = httpClient.query_string_from_dict(fields)
				returns:= "username=user&password=pass"
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: read_response_body_chunk
methods.description: Reads one chunk from the response.

methods.name: request
request_raw
methods.description:
Sends a raw request to the connected host. The URL parameter is just the part after the host, so for [code]http://somehost.com/index.php[/code], it is [code]index.php[/code].
				Headers are HTTP request headers. For available HTTP methods, see [code]METHOD_*[/code].
				Sends the body data raw, as a byte array and does not encode it in any way.

methods.name: set_read_chunk_size
methods.description: Sets the size of the buffer used and maximum bytes to read per iteration. see [method read_response_body_chunk]

constants.name: METHOD_GET
constants.description: HTTP GET method. The GET method requests a representation of the specified resource. Requests using GET should only retrieve data.

constants.name: METHOD_HEAD
constants.description: HTTP HEAD method. The HEAD method asks for a response identical to that of a GET request, but without the response body. This is useful to request metadata like HTTP headers or to check if a resource exists.

constants.name: METHOD_POST
constants.description: HTTP POST method. The POST method is used to submit an entity to the specified resource, often causing a change in state or side effects on the server. This is often used for forms and submitting data or uploading files.

constants.name: METHOD_PUT
constants.description: HTTP PUT method. The PUT method asks to replace all current representations of the target resource with the request payload. (You can think of [code]POST[/code] as "create or update" and [code]PUT[/code] as "update", although many services tend to not make a clear distinction or change their meaning).

constants.name: METHOD_DELETE
constants.description: HTTP DELETE method. The DELETE method requests to delete the specified resource.

constants.name: METHOD_OPTIONS
constants.description: HTTP OPTIONS method. The OPTIONS method asks for a description of the communication options for the target resource. Rarely used.

constants.name: METHOD_TRACE
constants.description: HTTP TRACE method. The TRACE method performs a message loop-back test along the path to the target resource. Returns the entire HTTP request received in the response body. Rarely used.

constants.name: METHOD_CONNECT
constants.description: HTTP CONNECT method. The CONNECT method establishes a tunnel to the server identified by the target resource. Rarely used.

constants.name: METHOD_PATCH
constants.description: HTTP PATCH method. The PATCH method is used to apply partial modifications to a resource.

constants.name: METHOD_MAX
constants.description: Marker for end of [code]METHOD_*[/code] enum. Not used.

constants.name: STATUS_DISCONNECTED
constants.description: Status: Disconnected from the server.

constants.name: STATUS_RESOLVING
constants.description: Status: Currently resolving the hostname for the given URL into an IP.

constants.name: STATUS_CANT_RESOLVE
constants.description: Status: DNS failure: Can't resolve the hostname for the given URL.

constants.name: STATUS_CONNECTING
constants.description: Status: Currently connecting to server.

constants.name: STATUS_CANT_CONNECT
constants.description: Status: Can't connect to the server.

constants.name: STATUS_CONNECTED
constants.description: Status: Connection established.

constants.name: STATUS_REQUESTING
constants.description: Status: Currently sending request.

constants.name: STATUS_BODY
constants.description: Status: HTTP body received.

constants.name: STATUS_CONNECTION_ERROR
constants.description: Status: Error in HTTP connection.

constants.name: STATUS_SSL_HANDSHAKE_ERROR
constants.description: Status: Error in SSL handshake.

constants.name: RESPONSE_CONTINUE
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]100 Continue[/code]. Interim response that indicates everything so far is OK and that the client should continue with the request (or ignore this status if already finished).

constants.name: RESPONSE_SWITCHING_PROTOCOLS
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]101 Switching Protocol[/code]. Sent in response to an [code]Upgrade[/code] request header by the client. Indicates the protocol the server is switching to.

constants.name: RESPONSE_PROCESSING
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]102 Processing[/code] (WebDAV). Indicates that the server has received and is processing the request, but no response is available yet.

constants.name: RESPONSE_OK
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]200 OK[/code]. The request has succeeded. Default response for successful requests. Meaning varies depending on the request. GET: The resource has been fetched and is transmitted in the message body. HEAD: The entity headers are in the message body. POST: The resource describing the result of the action is transmitted in the message body. TRACE: The message body contains the request message as received by the server.

constants.name: RESPONSE_CREATED
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]201 Created[/code]. The request has succeeded and a new resource has been created as a result of it. This is typically the response sent after a PUT request.

constants.name: RESPONSE_ACCEPTED
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]202 Accepted[/code]. The request has been received but not yet acted upon. It is non-committal, meaning that there is no way in HTTP to later send an asynchronous response indicating the outcome of processing the request. It is intended for cases where another process or server handles the request, or for batch processing.

constants.name: RESPONSE_NON_AUTHORITATIVE_INFORMATION
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]203 Non-Authoritative Information[/code]. This response code means returned meta-information set is not exact set as available from the origin server, but collected from a local or a third party copy. Except this condition, 200 OK response should be preferred instead of this response.

constants.name: RESPONSE_NO_CONTENT
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]204 No Content[/code]. There is no content to send for this request, but the headers may be useful. The user-agent may update its cached headers for this resource with the new ones.

constants.name: RESPONSE_RESET_CONTENT
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]205 Reset Content[/code]. The server has fulfilled the request and desires that the client resets the "document view" that caused the request to be sent to its original state as received from the origin server.

constants.name: RESPONSE_PARTIAL_CONTENT
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]206 Partial Content[/code]. This response code is used because of a range header sent by the client to separate download into multiple streams.

constants.name: RESPONSE_MULTI_STATUS
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]207 Multi-Status[/code] (WebDAV). A Multi-Status response conveys information about multiple resources in situations where multiple status codes might be appropriate.

constants.name: RESPONSE_ALREADY_REPORTED
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]208 Already Reported[/code] (WebDAV). Used inside a DAV: propstat response element to avoid enumerating the internal members of multiple bindings to the same collection repeatedly.

constants.name: RESPONSE_IM_USED
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]226 IM Used[/code] (WebDAV). The server has fulfilled a GET request for the resource, and the response is a representation of the result of one or more instance-manipulations applied to the current instance.

constants.name: RESPONSE_MULTIPLE_CHOICES
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]300 Multiple Choice[/code]. The request has more than one possible responses and there is no standardized way to choose one of the responses. User-agent or user should choose one of them.

constants.name: RESPONSE_MOVED_PERMANENTLY
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]301 Moved Permanently[/code]. Redirection. This response code means the URI of requested resource has been changed. The new URI is usually included in the response.

constants.name: RESPONSE_FOUND
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]302 Found[/code]. Temporary redirection. This response code means the URI of requested resource has been changed temporarily. New changes in the URI might be made in the future. Therefore, this same URI should be used by the client in future requests.

constants.name: RESPONSE_SEE_OTHER
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]303 See Other[/code]. The server is redirecting the user agent to a different resource, as indicated by a URI in the Location header field, which is intended to provide an indirect response to the original request.

constants.name: RESPONSE_NOT_MODIFIED
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]304 Not Modified[/code]. A conditional GET or HEAD request has been received and would have resulted in a 200 OK response if it were not for the fact that the condition evaluated to false.

constants.name: RESPONSE_USE_PROXY
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]305 Use Proxy[/code]. Deprecated. Do not use.

constants.name: RESPONSE_SWITCH_PROXY
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]306 Switch Proxy[/code]. Deprecated. Do not use.

constants.name: RESPONSE_TEMPORARY_REDIRECT
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]307 Temporary Redirect[/code]. The target resource resides temporarily under a different URI and the user agent MUST NOT change the request method if it performs an automatic redirection to that URI.

constants.name: RESPONSE_PERMANENT_REDIRECT
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]308 Permanent Redirect[/code]. The target resource has been assigned a new permanent URI and any future references to this resource ought to use one of the enclosed URIs.

constants.name: RESPONSE_BAD_REQUEST
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]400 Bad Request[/code]. The request was invalid. The server cannot or will not process the request due to something that is perceived to be a client error (e.g., malformed request syntax, invalid request message framing, invalid request contents, or deceptive request routing).

constants.name: RESPONSE_UNAUTHORIZED
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]401 Unauthorized[/code]. Credentials required. The request has not been applied because it lacks valid authentication credentials for the target resource.

constants.name: RESPONSE_PAYMENT_REQUIRED
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]402 Payment Required[/code]. This response code is reserved for future use. Initial aim for creating this code was using it for digital payment systems, however this is not currently used.

constants.name: RESPONSE_FORBIDDEN
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]403 Forbidden[/code]. The client does not have access rights to the content, i.e. they are unauthorized, so server is rejecting to give proper response. Unlike [code]401[/code], the client's identity is known to the server.

constants.name: RESPONSE_NOT_FOUND
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]404 Not Found[/code]. The server can not find requested resource. Either the URL is not recognized or the endpoint is valid but the resource itself does not exist. May also be sent instead of 403 to hide existence of a resource if the client is not authorized.

constants.name: RESPONSE_METHOD_NOT_ALLOWED
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]405 Method Not Allowed[/code]. The request's HTTP method is known by the server but has been disabled and cannot be used. For example, an API may forbid DELETE-ing a resource. The two mandatory methods, GET and HEAD, must never be disabled and should not return this error code.

constants.name: RESPONSE_NOT_ACCEPTABLE
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]406 Not Acceptable[/code]. The target resource does not have a current representation that would be acceptable to the user agent, according to the proactive negotiation header fields received in the request. Used when negotiation content.

constants.name: RESPONSE_PROXY_AUTHENTICATION_REQUIRED
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]407 Proxy Authentication Required[/code]. Similar to 401 Unauthorized, but it indicates that the client needs to authenticate itself in order to use a proxy.

constants.name: RESPONSE_REQUEST_TIMEOUT
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]408 Request Timeout[/code]. The server did not receive a complete request message within the time that it was prepared to wait.

constants.name: RESPONSE_CONFLICT
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]409 Conflict[/code]. The request could not be completed due to a conflict with the current state of the target resource. This code is used in situations where the user might be able to resolve the conflict and resubmit the request.

constants.name: RESPONSE_GONE
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]410 Gone[/code]. The target resource is no longer available at the origin server and this condition is likely permanent.

constants.name: RESPONSE_LENGTH_REQUIRED
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]411 Length Required[/code]. The server refuses to accept the request without a defined Content-Length header.

constants.name: RESPONSE_PRECONDITION_FAILED
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]412 Precondition Failed[/code]. One or more conditions given in the request header fields evaluated to false when tested on the server.

constants.name: RESPONSE_REQUEST_ENTITY_TOO_LARGE
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]413 Entity Too Large[/code]. The server is refusing to process a request because the request payload is larger than the server is willing or able to process.

constants.name: RESPONSE_REQUEST_URI_TOO_LONG
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]414 Request-URI Too Long[/code]. The server is refusing to service the request because the request-target is longer than the server is willing to interpret.

constants.name: RESPONSE_UNSUPPORTED_MEDIA_TYPE
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]415 Unsupported Media Type[/code]. The origin server is refusing to service the request because the payload is in a format not supported by this method on the target resource.

constants.name: RESPONSE_REQUESTED_RANGE_NOT_SATISFIABLE
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]416 Requested Range Not Satisfiable[/code]. None of the ranges in the request's Range header field overlap the current extent of the selected resource or the set of ranges requested has been rejected due to invalid ranges or an excessive request of small or overlapping ranges.

constants.name: RESPONSE_EXPECTATION_FAILED
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]417 Expectation Failed[/code]. The expectation given in the request's Expect header field could not be met by at least one of the inbound servers.

constants.name: RESPONSE_IM_A_TEAPOT
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]418 I'm A Teapot[/code]. Any attempt to brew coffee with a teapot should result in the error code "418 I'm a teapot". The resulting entity body MAY be short and stout.

constants.name: RESPONSE_MISDIRECTED_REQUEST
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]421 Misdirected Request[/code]. The request was directed at a server that is not able to produce a response. This can be sent by a server that is not configured to produce responses for the combination of scheme and authority that are included in the request URI.

constants.name: RESPONSE_UNPROCESSABLE_ENTITY
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]422 Unprocessable Entity[/code] (WebDAV). The server understands the content type of the request entity (hence a 415 Unsupported Media Type status code is inappropriate), and the syntax of the request entity is correct (thus a 400 Bad Request status code is inappropriate) but was unable to process the contained instructions.

constants.name: RESPONSE_LOCKED
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]423 Locked[/code] (WebDAV). The source or destination resource of a method is locked.

constants.name: RESPONSE_FAILED_DEPENDENCY
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]424 Failed Dependency[/code] (WebDAV). The method could not be performed on the resource because the requested action depended on another action and that action failed.

constants.name: RESPONSE_UPGRADE_REQUIRED
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]426 Upgrade Required[/code]. The server refuses to perform the request using the current protocol but might be willing to do so after the client upgrades to a different protocol.

constants.name: RESPONSE_PRECONDITION_REQUIRED
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]428 Precondition Required[/code]. The origin server requires the request to be conditional.

constants.name: RESPONSE_TOO_MANY_REQUESTS
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]429 Too Many Requests[/code]. The user has sent too many requests in a given amount of time (see "rate limiting"). Back off and increase time between requests or try again later.

constants.name: RESPONSE_REQUEST_HEADER_FIELDS_TOO_LARGE
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]431 Rquest Header Fields Too Large[/code]. The server is unwilling to process the request because its header fields are too large. The request MAY be resubmitted after reducing the size of the request header fields.

constants.name: RESPONSE_UNAVAILABLE_FOR_LEGAL_REASONS
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]451 Response Unavailable For Legal Reasons[/code]. The server is denying access to the resource as a consequence of a legal demand.

constants.name: RESPONSE_INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]500 Internal Server Error[/code]. The server encountered an unexpected condition that prevented it from fulfilling the request.

constants.name: RESPONSE_NOT_IMPLEMENTED
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]501 Not Implemented[/code]. The server does not support the functionality required to fulfill the request.

constants.name: RESPONSE_BAD_GATEWAY
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]502 Bad Gateway[/code]. The server, while acting as a gateway or proxy, received an invalid response from an inbound server it accessed while attempting to fulfill the request. Usually returned by load balancers or proxies.

constants.name: RESPONSE_SERVICE_UNAVAILABLE
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]503 Service Unavailable[/code]. The server is currently unable to handle the request due to a temporary overload or scheduled maintenance, which will likely be alleviated after some delay. Try again later.

constants.name: RESPONSE_GATEWAY_TIMEOUT
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]504 Gateway Timeout[/code]. The server, while acting as a gateway or proxy, did not receive a timely response from an upstream server it needed to access in order to complete the request. Usually returned by load balancers or proxies.

constants.name: RESPONSE_HTTP_VERSION_NOT_SUPPORTED
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]505 HTTP Version Not Supported[/code]. The server does not support, or refuses to support, the major version of HTTP that was used in the request message.

constants.name: RESPONSE_VARIANT_ALSO_NEGOTIATES
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]506 Variant Also Negotiates[/code]. The server has an internal configuration error: the chosen variant resource is configured to engage in transparent content negotiation itself, and is therefore not a proper end point in the negotiation process.

constants.name: RESPONSE_INSUFFICIENT_STORAGE
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]507 Insufficient Storage[/code]. The method could not be performed on the resource because the server is unable to store the representation needed to successfully complete the request.

constants.name: RESPONSE_LOOP_DETECTED
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]508 Loop Detected[/code]. The server terminated an operation because it encountered an infinite loop while processing a request with "Depth: infinity". This status indicates that the entire operation failed.

constants.name: RESPONSE_NOT_EXTENDED
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]510 Not Extended[/code]. The policy for accessing the resource has not been met in the request. The server should send back all the information necessary for the client to issue an extended request.

constants.name: RESPONSE_NETWORK_AUTH_REQUIRED
constants.description: HTTP status code [code]511 Network Authentication Required[/code]. The client needs to authenticate to gain network access.

AudioEffectEQ6.name: AudioEffectEQ6
AudioEffectEQ6.brief_description:
Adds a 6-band equalizer audio effect to an Audio bus. Gives you control over frequencies from 32 Hz to 10000 Hz.
		Each frequency can be modulated between -60/+24 dB.
AudioEffectEQ6.description:
Frequency bands :
		Band 1 : 32 Hz
		Band 2 : 100 Hz
		Band 3 : 320 Hz
		Band 4 : 1000 Hz
		Band 5 : 3200 Hz
		Band 6 : 10000 Hz

		See also [AudioEffectEQ], [AudioEffectEQ10], [AudioEffectEQ21].

GradientTexture.name: GradientTexture
GradientTexture.description: Uses a [Gradient] to fill the texture data, the gradient will be filled from left to right using colors obtained from the gradient, this means that the texture does not necessarily represent an exact copy of the gradient, but instead an interpolation of samples obtained from the gradient at fixed steps (see [method set_width]).

properties.name: gradient
properties.description: The [Gradient] that will be used to fill the texture.

properties.name: width
properties.description: The number of color samples that will be obtained from the [Gradient].

InstancePlaceholder.name: InstancePlaceholder
InstancePlaceholder.brief_description: Placeholder for the root [Node] of a [PackedScene].
InstancePlaceholder.description:
Turning on the option [b]Load As Placeholder[/b] for an instanced scene in the editor causes it to be replaced by an InstacePlaceholder when running the game. This makes it possible to delay actually loading the scene until calling [method replace_by_instance]. This is useful to avoid loading large scenes all at once by loading parts of it selectively.
		The InstancePlaceholder does not have a transform. This causes any child nodes to be positioned relatively to the Viewport from point (0,0), rather than their parent as displayed in the editor. Replacing the placeholder with a scene with a transform will transform children relatively to their parent again.

methods.name: get_instance_path
methods.description: Retrieve the path to the [PackedScene] resource file that is loaded by default when calling [method replace_by_instance].

methods.name: replace_by_instance
methods.description: Replace this placeholder by the scene handed as an argument, or the original scene if no argument is given. As for all resources, the scene is loaded only if it's not loaded already. By manually loading the scene beforehand, delays caused by this function can be avoided.

VisualScriptBuiltinFunc.name: VisualScriptBuiltinFunc
VisualScriptBuiltinFunc.brief_description: A Visual Script node used to call built-in functions.
VisualScriptBuiltinFunc.description:
A built-in function used inside a [VisualScript]. It is usually a math function or an utility function.
		See also [@GDScript], for the same functions in the GDScript language.
